stylometry: @RISK works by taking potential situations that may happen and telling you the level of risk you are inquiring by choosing each possible situation. It gives you the best insight as to which path is the safest when making a possible risky desicion. When you run a simulation with 5 inputs, that means you are testing 5 different possible scenerios in your simulation. You will recieve the probable outcome for each one of those 5 possibile choices. The data is analyized by looking at 4 main concepts: STD-DEV which tells you how relaible the information for that simulation is, MEAN profit which is the average profit you will be incurring, MAX potential profit, and MIN potential profit. The most important aspect of the analysis is the STD-DEV because if that number is really high, then the numbers you are looking at are not reliable and you should probably not really consider that choice.
